    title: "Trichomoniasis",
    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Trichomoniasis", content: "Trichomoniasis is the most common curable sexually transmitted infection worldwide, caused by the flagellated protozoan parasite Trichomonas vaginalis that colonizes the squamous epithelium of the urogenital tract. The organism adheres to vaginal epithelial cells via surface adhesin proteins, causing contact-dependent cytolysis through the release of cell-detaching factor, cysteine proteases, and lytic pore-forming proteins. In women, infection produces vulvovaginal irritation, dysuria, and a characteristic frothy, yellow-green, malodorous discharge with a vaginal pH above 4.5 — the 'strawberry cervix' (colpitis macularis) from punctate hemorrhages is pathognomonic but seen in only 2% of cases on naked-eye examination. Diagnosis is made by wet mount microscopy (motile trichomonads with jerky movements, 60-70% sensitivity), nucleic acid amplification testing (NAAT, >95% sensitivity), or rapid antigen testing — treatment is oral metronidazole or tinidazole for both patient and sexual partners, with abstinence from alcohol during treatment and 72 hours after due to disulfiram-like reaction." },
