    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Tricuspid Atresia", content: "Tricuspid atresia is a congenital heart defect characterized by complete absence of the tricuspid valve, with no direct communication between the right atrium and right ventricle. Survival depends on two obligatory shunts: an atrial septal defect (or patent foramen ovale) allowing right-to-left shunting of systemic venous blood from the right atrium to the left atrium, and either a ventricular septal defect or patent ductus arteriosus providing pulmonary blood flow. The clinical presentation depends on the presence and size of the VSD and the relationship of the great arteries: normally related great arteries with a restrictive VSD produce severe cyanosis from decreased pulmonary blood flow, while transposition of the great arteries with a large VSD may produce heart failure from excessive pulmonary blood flow. The neonatal management includes prostaglandin E1 infusion to maintain ductal patency until surgical palliation. Staged surgical palliation typically involves a modified Blalock-Taussig shunt (systemic-to-pulmonary artery shunt in the neonatal period), bidirectional Glenn shunt (superior vena cava to pulmonary artery at 4-6 months), and Fontan completion (inferior vena cava to pulmonary artery at 2-4 years). The RN monitors oxygen saturation, administers prostaglandin E1 and monitors for side effects (apnea, fever, hypotension), assesses for signs of inadequate pulmonary or systemic blood flow, provides pre- and post-operative nursing care, and educates families about the staged surgical approach." },
