    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Down Syndrome (Trisomy 21)", content: "Down syndrome is the most common chromosomal disorder, occurring in approximately 1 in 700 live births, caused by the presence of an extra copy of chromosome 21 (trisomy 21) resulting from meiotic nondisjunction (95%), Robertsonian translocation (3-4%), or mosaicism (1-2%). The additional genetic material from chromosome 21 leads to overexpression of genes affecting neurodevelopment, cardiac morphogenesis, immune function, and cellular metabolism — the DYRK1A gene is particularly implicated in intellectual disability through effects on neurogenesis and synaptic plasticity. Characteristic features include hypotonia, epicanthal folds, flat facial profile, single palmar crease, sandal gap toe deformity, and intellectual disability ranging from mild to moderate. Associated medical conditions include congenital heart defects (40-50%, especially atrioventricular septal defects), atlantoaxial instability, hypothyroidism, hearing and vision problems, celiac disease, and significantly increased risk of acute lymphoblastic leukemia — regular health surveillance following AAP guidelines is essential." },
